abor unrest, and the motley, unglamorous work of small-time operatives. He then goes on to show us how writers like Dashiell Hammett and editors of sensational pulp magazines like Black Mask embellished on actual experiences and fashioned an image of the PI as a compelling, even admirable, necessary evil, doing society’s dirty work while adhering to a self-imposed moral code. Scandals, public investigations, and regulations brought the boom years of private agencies to an end in the late 1930s, Walton explains, in the process fully cementing the shift from reality to fantasy. Today, as the private detective has long since given way to security services and armed guards, the myth of the lone PI remains as potent as ever. No fan of crime fiction or American history will want to miss The Legendary Detective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPrivate investigators - United States - History. 0aPrivate investigatorszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aprivate eye, detective, mystery, crime, sleuth, detection, investigation, sociology, literature, history, hardboiled, noir, pinkerton, pulp fiction, dashiell hammett, black mask, scandal, regulation, licensing, armed guards, security services, agency, nonfiction, masculinity, loner, isolation, society, corruption, popular culture, william j burns, charlie siringo, nick harris.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226308432423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226308432/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles